title: For Sale:  Alexander Arms Tactical Blade Trigger - Price Drop (again)
postcontent:
This trigger has approximately 100 rounds on it.  It sells new for $203.50 from Alexander Arms.  I'm not including the pins, but if you're replacing a trigger in your AR, you should have the pins already.

This tactical trigger unit has been designed specifically for field use and does not share a common heritage with a target trigger. For this reason, it is not recommended for target-type shooting, although it may be used with some success in this discipline. The trigger is basically a single stage unit with a bushing mounted disconnector, which is adjustable for engagement and over travel while the pull weight and disconnector engagement are fixed to ensure durability during hard use and inclement environments.

The trigger bow is intentionally narrower than those commonly found on target type triggers. This assists with accurate reference of the trigger finger if the unit is used with gloves or in cold/wet conditions. The pull weight allows manipulation of the trigger with gloves while minimizing the possibility of discharging a round unexpectedly in the manner of a target trigger. In extreme cold conditions the trigger can still be used with mitts with the trigger guard pivoted down, although this is not recommended.

The unit is manufactured from an S7 type tool steel and is through-hardened to provide a durable base. The surface is chrome-plated using a technique that creates a dense finish and a surface hardness in excess of 72 HRC. This surface provides the durability for the trigger in adverse conditions and, hence, the surfaces on both the trigger and the hammer should not be further polished or honed.

title: For Trade:  Colt 1911 Original WWI from 1918, Great Collectible Shooter
postcontent:
I have an original Colt M1911 USGI from WWI that I am looking to trade. This gun shoots amazingly well for being almost 100 years old - nothing less than expected from an original Colt! The serial number on the frame traces to 1918, and the slide with the REAR rampant Colt is from 1915-ish to late 1917. There is an AA mark on the slide, meaning it went through an arsenal rebuild at Augusta Arsenal sometime after WWI, as did many USGI WWI and WWII firearms. Once there, they parkerized it and swapped out any faulty or damaged parts and put it back into service. Seeing how arsenal rebuilds focused more on functional parts and not keeping its original parts for collectibles, a lot of parts were mismatched. I do not know enough about the parts on it, but I do know the grips and the slide stop were replaced with later versions. The mainspring housing is still original to the gun and is not a 1911A1 housing. The gun likely  received the earlier slide and plastic Coltwood grips at Augusta as well. It is not a correct Colt 1918 M1911, but is what would many would consider a collectible shooter. 

I fired around 30 rounds through it after I received it and it shoots amazingly great for such an old gun. Very accurate. I was hitting steel at around 50 yards with it. The only "damage" to it is the off-coloring on the left side, near the muzzle. From the best I can tell, it does not appear to be rust, and is barely noticeable. Has all correct military markings and nice rifling in the barrel. Both slide and frame lock up great. Pistol includes 2 unmarked 7-round magazines. 

I also upgraded all of the springs in it because I did not know when the last time it received and upgrade on the mechanical/operational parts. Like I said, it shoots great and I hate to get rid of it because I love the gun and its history, but want to try something different.

The picture is a different pistol, but mine almost looks like it. The difference is the Colt is on the rear of the left side, by the hammer. Original pics to follow this weekend. Please let me know if you are interested. Thanks.

title: For Trade:  COLT 1911 ORIGINAL WWI FROM 1918, GREAT COLLECTIBLE SHOOTER
postcontent:
I have an original Colt M1911 USGI from WWI that I am looking to trade. This gun shoots amazingly well for being almost 100 years old - nothing less than expected from an original Colt! The serial number on the frame traces to 1918, and the slide with the rear rampant Colt is from 1914 to late 1917. The AA mark on the slide means that it went through an arsenal rebuild at Augusta Arsenal sometime after the war, as did many USGI WWI and WWII firearms. Once there, they parkerized it and swapped out any faulty or damaged parts and put it back into service. Post-war arsenals rebuilds focused more on functional parts and not keeping its original parts for collectibles, a lot of parts were mismatched. I do not know enough about the parts on it, but I do know the grips and the slide stop were replaced with later versions. The mainspring housing is still original to the gun. The gun likely received the Coltwood grips at Augusta as well. It is what would many would consider a collectible shooter. 

I fired around 30 rounds through it after I received it and it shoots great and is very accurate. The only "damage" to it is a little off-coloring on the left side, near the muzzle. In my opinion, it does not appear to be rust or pitting, but is likely discoloration of the metal. All in all, it is barely noticeable. Has all correct military markings and nice rifling in the barrel. Both slide and frame lock up great. Pistol includes 2 unmarked 7-round magazines and blue Colt box.

I replaced the springs in it because I did not know when the last time it received and upgrade on the mechanical/operational parts. Like I said, it shoots great and I hate to get rid of it because I love the gun and its history, but want to try something different.

More pictures can be found here:

http://s1337.photobucket.com/user/carsoca2/library/Colt%201911?sort=6&page=1

Please let me know if you are interested. Thanks.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Ruger Security Six was a .357 Magnum/.38 Special revolver
location: Roanoke County, Christiansburg, Blacksburg, Roanoke, Virginia
postcontent:
Caliber: .38 S&W, .38 Special, .357 Magnum, 
Capacity: 6 round cylinder 
Fire Modes: DA Revolver 
original owner, maybe 200 rounds shot through it since owned. Includes leather holster (R).  Will consider sale or trade for a semiauto handgun of equal value +/- $

The Ruger Security Six was a .357 Magnum/.38 Special revolver introduced in 1968. It had adjustable rear sights and was designed as Ruger's flagship offering for the double action revolver market. They were very popular because they were well built and were competitively priced as compared to similar Colt or Smith & Wesson models. The First Security Six Revolvers were offered in Cobalt Blued finish. Starting in 1975, Ruger offered the Security Six in a stainless Steel version.
However, and this is the real reason why these guns are a solid buy, they will simply out last any other DA revolver over thousands of Magnum rounds. (With the exception, of course, of Ruger’s follow-on piece, the GP-100.) If one bought a Security Six, one could expect a lifetime of full use and still be able to hand it to one’s children with nary a problem. I once knew of an indoor range that had one as a rental gun and it digested, by their estimate, some 1,400,000 rounds with no parts breakages and minimal maintenance. That is the essence of a good deal!
